summary:
Fixed the race-condition bug in the counter.

Problem  
incrementCounter did a read-modify-write:
1. GET current value
2. value + 1
3. SET new value

When many requests ran concurrently, multiple workers could read the same value before any wrote it back, so some increments were lost and the test failed.

Fix  
Use Redis’ atomic INCR command, which increments the key and returns the new value in a single atomic operation.

Changed app/counter.js:

```diff
-// Read-modify-write implementation
-const current = await client.get(COUNTER_KEY);
-const value   = parseInt(current || "0", 10);
-const newValue = value + 1;
-await client.set(COUNTER_KEY, newValue.toString());
-
-logger.debug(`Counter incremented: ${value} -> ${newValue}`);
-return newValue;
+// Atomic increment
+const newValue = await client.incr(COUNTER_KEY);
+logger.debug(`Counter incremented -> ${newValue}`);
+return newValue;
```

Running ./test.sh now prints:

Expected: 100  
Got:      100  
PASS: Counter is correct
